{"title_page": "Jaren Jackson Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{about|the active basketball player|his father, the basketball coach and former player|Jaren Jackson}} <!--Hatnote since this page is the top Google result for \"Jaren Jackson\" -->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jaren Jackson Jr.\n| image = 20170329 MCDAAG Jaren Jackson Jr. inbounds.jpg\n| caption = Jackson at the [[2017 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2017 McDonald's All-American Game]]\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]] \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 242\n| number = 13\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Memphis Grizzlies\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1999|9|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Plainfield, New Jersey]]<!-- Place of birth confirmed by linked USA Basketball bio -->\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = \n* [[La Lumiere School]]<br>([[La Porte, Indiana]])\n* [[Park Tudor School|Park Tudor]]<br>([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n| college = [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year   = 2018\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 4\n| draft_team   = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| highlights =\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Team|NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] Defensive Player of the Year (2018)\n* Big Ten Freshman of the Year (2018)\n* Third-team All-Big Ten (2018)\n* Big Ten All-Freshman Team (2018)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2017 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2017]])\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2017)\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2017)\n| nba_profile = jaren_jackson\n| bbr = jacksja02\n}}\n'''Jaren Walter Jackson Jr.''' (born September 15, 1999) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State Spartans]]. He was selected by Memphis with the fourth overall pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]].\n\n==High school career==\nJackson started his high school career with [[Park Tudor School|Park Tudor School]]. He played varsity for three years, where he averaged 10 points a game, 6 rebounds a game, and 3 blocks a game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athlete/jaren-jackson/543Mzlz0EeOzMAAmVebBJg/gendersport/basketball-stats.htm|title=Jaren Jackson's High School Basketball Stats|website=MaxPreps.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Jackson won two [[Indiana High School Athletic Association|IHSAA]] state basketball championships while at Park Tudor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Class 2A: Park Tudor wins 4th title in 5 years|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/high-school/2015/03/28/class-park-tudor-repeats-win-frankton/70597226/|website=Indystar.com|publisher=Indy Star|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He  was teammates with former [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier University]] standout and current [[New Orleans Pelicans]] [[two-way contract|two-way player]] [[Trevon Bluiett]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Park Tudor: 84 Westview:57|url=http://wishtv.com/2014/03/29/park-tudor-84-westview-57/|publisher=Wish TV|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He then transferred to [[La Lumiere School]] for his senior year,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verbalcommits.com/players/jaren-jackson-jr|title=Verbal Commits {{!}} Jaren Jackson, Jr. Player Profile, Highlights, Offers, Twitter|website=www.verbalcommits.com|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> where he started for their varsity squad.\n\n===Recruiting===\nJackson was considered one of the top players in the 2017 graduating class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbadraft.net/players/jaren-jackson-jr|title=Jaren Jackson Jr. {{!}} NBADraft.net|website=www.nbadraft.net|language=en|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Scout.com ranked Jackson the 5th best player nationally,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scout.com/player/193446-jaren-jackson|title=Jaren Jackson, La Lumiere School PF - Scout|website=www.scout.com|language=en|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> 1st in his respective position, and 2nd overall in the midwest region. 247 Sports ranked him 7th nationally,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Player/Jaren-Jackson-78413|title=Jaren Jackson, La Lumiere School , Power Forward|website=247Sports|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> being 4th in his position. ESPN ranked him 8th in the ESPN 100,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/207895/jaren-jackson|title=Jaren Jackson - Basketball Recruiting - Player Profiles - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> being 2nd in his position and 2nd regionally. \n{{College athlete recruit start|40=no|collapse=no|year=2017}}{{College athlete recruit entry|40=|247 stars=5|feet=6|highschool=[[La Lumiere School]] \n[[Park Tudor School]]|hometown=[[Carmel, Indiana]]|inches=10|position=PF|recruit=Jaren Jackson Jr.|weight=226|commitdate=September 15, 2016|espn grade=93|rivals stars=5|scout stars=5}}{{College athlete recruit end|247 overall=7|rivals overall=6|espn overall=8}} Jackson was recruited by a number of notable programs, including Michigan State, Notre Dame, Butler, Indiana, Purdue, Maryland, and several more.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/high-school/2016/07/03/jaren-jackson-jr-helps-usa-u17-team-gold/86659816/|title=Jaren Jackson Jr. helps USA U17 team to gold|newspaper=Indianapolis Star|language=en|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref> He was invited to partake in the [[McDonald's All-American Game]] played on March 29, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.landof10.com/michigan-state/michigan-state-jaren-jackson-jr-brian-bowen-mcdonalds-all-american|title=Michigan State signee Jaren Jackson Jr. reacts to McDonald's selection|date=January 22, 2017|newspaper=Land of 10|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nOn September 15, 2016, Jaren Jackson Jr. announced his intentions to play for [[Tom Izzo]] at [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]]. He signed the [[letter of intent]] on November 9, 2016.<ref name=\":0\" /> Jackson would make his collegiate debut on November 10, 2017, recording 13 points and a season-high 13 rebounds in a blowout 98\u201366 win over the [[North Florida Ospreys men's basketball|North Florida Ospreys]]. Four days later, he would record a then-season-high 19 points in an 88\u201381 loss to the #1 ranked [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke Blue Devils]]. On December 5, Jackson would put up 11 points and a career-high 8 blocks in a 62\u201352 win over the [[Rutgers Scarlet Knights men's basketball|Rutgers Scarlet Knights]]. Four days later, he would record 17 points and another career-high 13 rebounds in a blowout 88\u201363 win over the [[Southern Utah Thunderbirds men's basketball|Southern Utah Thunderbirds]]. On January 22, 2018, Jackson recorded a then-season-high 21 points to go with 11 rebounds and 6 blocks in an 87\u201374 win over the [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois Fighting Illini]]. On February 13, he would put up a career-high 27 points in a blowout 87\u201357 win over the [[Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball|Minnesota Golden Gophers]]. At the end of the regular season for Michigan State, he would be named both the Big Ten's Defensive Player of the Year, Freshman of the Year,  Big Ten's All-Freshman Team, and the All-Big Ten's Third Team. On April 2, Jackson would declare his entry into the [[2018 NBA draft]], where he was considered a potential top-tier lottery selection.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Memphis Grizzlies (2018\u2013present)===\nOn June 21, 2018, Jackson was selected with the fourth overall pick by the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] in the [[2018 NBA draft]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2774199-jaren-jackson-picked-by-grizzlies-no-4-in-nba-draft-twitter-loves-upside |title = Jaren Jackson Picked by Grizzlies No. 4 in NBA Draft; Twitter Loves Upside}}</ref> On July 1, 2018, he signed a multi-year, rookie scale contract with the Grizzlies.<ref>{{cite web |title=Memphis Grizzlies sign Jaren Jackson Jr. to multi-year contract |url=https://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/memphis-grizzlies-sign-jaren-jackson-jr-to-multi-year-contract-180701 |website=NBA.com |accessdate=July 2, 2018 |date=July 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 29, 2019, Jackson was shut down for the remainder of the season due to a deep bruise to his right thigh.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://twitter.com/mgiannotto/status/1111663747066675202 | title=Memphis Grizzlies coach JB Bickerstaff just confirmed that Jaren Jackson Jr. and Kyle Anderson won't play the rest of this season}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nJackson helped the United States of America's under-17 basketball team win the gold medal at the FIBA 2016 World Championships; in which he scored two points and had six rebounds. He averaged 4.3 points, 5.2 rebounds, 1.2 blocked shots, and shot 53 percent from the field.<ref name=\":0\" /> He was a member of the USA Junior National Select Team that participated in the 2017 [[Nike Hoop Summit]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]. Coming off the bench, Jackson tallied 13 points and a game-high nine rebounds in 25 minutes of play.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usab.com/news-events/live-stats/2017/usa-vs-world-select-team-2017.aspx|title=LiveStats - USA vs World Select Team - Nike Hoop Summit|access-date=April 8, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 58 || 56 || 26.1 || .506 || .359 || .766 || 4.7 || 1.1 || .9 || 1.4 || 13.8\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 58 || 56 || 26.1 || .506 || .359 || .766 || 4.7 || 1.1 || .9 || 1.4 || 13.8\n{{S-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Michigan State Spartans men's basketball team|Michigan State]]\n| 33 || 32 || 22.2 || .520 || .396 || .797 || 5.8 || 1.2 || .6 || 3.2 || 11.3\n{{S-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is the son of former professional basketball coach and former NBA player [[Jaren Jackson]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{basketballstats|bbr=j/jacksja02}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180806225354/http://www.msuspartans.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/jaren_jackson_jr_1058097.html Michigan State Spartans bio]\n*[https://www.usab.com/basketball/players/mens/j/jackson-jr-jaren.aspx USA Basketball bio]\n\n{{Memphis Grizzlies current roster}}\n{{2018 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jackson, Jaren Jr.}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Centers (basketball)]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Memphis Grizzlies draft picks]]\n[[Category:Memphis Grizzlies players]]\n[[Category:Michigan State Spartans men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Park Tudor School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:La Lumiere School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{about|the active basketball player|his father, the basketball coach and former player|Jaren Jackson}} <!--Hatnote since this page is the top Google result for \"Jaren Jackson\" -->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Jaren Jackson Jr.\n| image = 20170329 MCDAAG Jaren Jackson Jr. inbounds.jpg\n| caption = Jackson at the [[2017 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2017 McDonald's All-American Game]]\n| position = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]] / [[Center (basketball)|Center]] \n| height_ft = 7\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lb = 242\n| number = 13\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Memphis Grizzlies\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1999|9|15}}\n| birth_place = [[Plainfield, New Jersey]]<!-- Place of birth confirmed by linked USA Basketball bio -->\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = \n* [[La Lumiere School]]<br>([[La Porte, Indiana]])\n* [[Park Tudor School|Park Tudor]]<br>([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n| college = [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]] (2017\u20132018)\n| draft_year   = 2018\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 4\n| draft_team   = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| career_start = 2018\n| years1 = {{nbay|2018|start}}\u2013present\n| team1 = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| highlights =\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Team|NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] Defensive Player of the Year (2018)\n* Big Ten Freshman of the Year (2018)\n* Third-team All-Big Ten (2018)\n* Big Ten All-Freshman Team (2018)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2017 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2017]])\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2017)\n* [[Nike Hoop Summit]] (2017)\n| nba_profile = jaren_jackson\n| bbr = jacksja02\n}}\n'''Jaren Walter Jackson Jr.''' (born September 15, 1999) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He played [[college basketball]] for the [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State Spartans]]. He was selected by Memphis with the fourth overall pick of the [[2018 NBA draft]].\n\n==High school career==\nJackson started his high school career with [[Park Tudor School|Park Tudor School]]. He played varsity for three years, where he averaged 10 points a game, 6 rebounds a game, and 3 blocks a game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athlete/jaren-jackson/543Mzlz0EeOzMAAmVebBJg/gendersport/basketball-stats.htm|title=Jaren Jackson's High School Basketball Stats|website=MaxPreps.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Jackson won two [[Indiana High School Athletic Association|IHSAA]] state basketball championships while at Park Tudor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Class 2A: Park Tudor wins 4th title in 5 years|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/high-school/2015/03/28/class-park-tudor-repeats-win-frankton/70597226/|website=Indystar.com|publisher=Indy Star|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He  was teammates with former [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier University]] standout and current [[New Orleans Pelicans]] [[two-way contract|two-way player]] [[Trevon Bluiett]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Park Tudor: 84 Westview:57|url=http://wishtv.com/2014/03/29/park-tudor-84-westview-57/|publisher=Wish TV|accessdate=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He then transferred to [[La Lumiere School]] for his senior year,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.verbalcommits.com/players/jaren-jackson-jr|title=Verbal Commits {{!}} Jaren Jackson, Jr. Player Profile, Highlights, Offers, Twitter|website=www.verbalcommits.com|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> where he started for their varsity squad.\n\n===Recruiting===\nJackson was considered one of the top players in the 2017 graduating class.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbadraft.net/players/jaren-jackson-jr|title=Jaren Jackson Jr. {{!}} NBADraft.net|website=www.nbadraft.net|language=en|access-date=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Scout.com ranked Jackson the 5th best player nationally,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scout.com/player/193446-jaren-jackson|title=Jaren Jackson, La Lumiere School PF - Scout|website=www.scout